<m:mo> - </m:mo> 
<m:mi> y </m:mi>
<m:mo> ) </m:mo> 
<m:mo> = </m:mo> 
<m:mo> { </m:mo> 
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:mi> h </m:mi>
</m:mrow>
<m:mrow>
<m:mo> ( </m:mo> 
<m:mi> h </m:mi>
<m:mo> - </m:mo> 
<m:mi> y </m:mi>
<m:mo> ) </m:mo> 
</m:mrow>
</m:mfrac>
<m:mo> - </m:mo> 
<m:mn> 4 </m:mn>
<m:mi> y </m:mi>
<m:mo> } </m:mo> 
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-130">
Evidently, this is an equation in two variables and hence can not be solved. It is this precise limitation of conventional approach that we switched to fraction approach to get an equation in one variable,
</para>
<para id="element-131"><m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mo> ⇒ </m:mo> 
<m:mo> ( </m:mo> 
